Project Topic and Overview¶

This project will look at prediction and classification of obesity levels based off of eating habits, physical condition, lifestyle, and other factors.

Overview of Project Models¶

This project will look at three different models.

  1. The first model will use OLS Regression. This method is one of the simpler approaches and we will show that it does not perform very well. This model will be used in contrast to more sophisticated supervised machine learning methods. While this method fails in doing an adequate job at predicting, we will show that other models are more succesful.
  2. The next model will use the ensemble method of Random Forests that was covered in lecture.
  3. Lastly, we will look at gradient boosting with XGBoost. The method was mentioned in lecture, but not covered in detail.

Goals¶

The main goal of this project is to be able to predict or classify accurately based on the features provided. The orginal dataset has 16 features and was obtained by survey. Nearly all features were binary or ordinal values. These categorical values along with response bias pose a challenge in ensuring that the model(s) are accurate.

A secondary goal is to show a comparison of a simple model vs. more advanced models. We will show where the simple model fails and discuss alternative options.

Data Source¶

The dataset is called Estimation of Obesity Levels Based On Eating Habits and Physical Condition and is from the UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository. The dataset and more information about it can be found at the following link:

https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/544/estimation+of+obesity+levels+based+on+eating+habits+and+physical+condition

According to the description, the dataset includes "data for the estimation of obesity levels in individuals from the countries of Mexico, Peru and Colombia, based on their eating habits and physical condition. The data contains 17 attributes and 2111 records, the records are labeled with the class variable NObesity (Obesity Level), that allows classification of the data using the values of Insufficient Weight, Normal Weight, Overweight Level I, Overweight Level II, Obesity Type I, Obesity Type II and Obesity Type III. 77% of the data was generated synthetically using the Weka tool and the SMOTE filter, 23% of the data was collected directly from users through a web platform."

There is also an introductory paper that accompanies the dataset that can be found at the following link:

https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Dataset-for-estimation-of-obesity-levels-based-on-Palechor-Manotas/35b40bacd2ffa9370885b7a3004d88995fd1d011

Revising the Weight/Obesity Categories¶

According to the paper, the categories should follow:

  • Underweight: Less than 18.5
  • Normal: 18.5 to 24.9
  • Overweight: 25.0 to 29.9
  • Obesity I: 30.0 to 34.9
  • Obesity II: 35.0 to 39.9
  • Obesity III: Higher than 40

Not only are there misclassifications and inconsistent category values, but the number of categories are different as well. We'll update these categories and ranges.

In [8]:
#function to assign the proper category using bmi
def bmi_to_class(bmi):
    if bmi < 18.5:
        return 'Underweight'
    elif 18.5 <= bmi < 25.0:
        return 'Normal'
    elif 25.0 <= bmi < 30.0:
        return 'Overweight'
    elif 30.0 <= bmi < 35.0:
        return 'Obesity_I'
    elif 35.0 <= bmi < 40.0:
        return 'Obesity_II'
    else:
        return 'Obesity_III'
In [9]:
#applies function and creates a new column of the proper categories
data['obesity_class'] = data['bmi'].apply(bmi_to_class)

#function to get unique values from each column
def get_unique_col_values(data):
  uniqueColVal = {column: data[column].unique() for column in data.columns}
  for column, values in uniqueColVal.items():
    print(f'{column}: {values}')
  return

Nearly all of the survey options were categorical, so it is strange that there are non-integer numeric values as responses. Similarly, some age values were submitted as integers while others were not.

We will take the floor of each numerical cell to convert to integer values (We will exclude bmi since it is continuous and correctly so).

In [13]:
#finds the floor of every numeric column but bmi
numCols = data.select_dtypes(include = [np.number]).columns.drop('bmi')

data[numCols] = data[numCols].apply(np.floor)

One Hot Encoding¶

Next we need to one hot encode transport_type since they are not ordinal.

In [21]:
#one hot encodes the transport type column. This turns the column into 5 new ones
#within a new dataframe
encoder = OneHotEncoder()
encodedTransport = encoder.fit_transform(data[['transport_type']])

encodedTransport_df = pd.DataFrame(encodedTransport.toarray(), columns = encoder.get_feature_names_out(['transport_type']))

Variance Inflation Factor (VIF)¶

Next we will form a matrix, $X$, and vector, $y$. These will be used in later sections. We can use the variance inflation factor to narrow down our predictors while reducing the likelihood of collinearity. Our threshold for vif is 5, which is a bit on the conservative side. We will drop the predictors with the highest vif until we are left with all predictors where their corresponding vif is less than 5.

In [33]:
#creates matrix X and vector y
X = features_df
y = dataFinal['bmi']

The following function will create a dataframe of the features and vif values so that we can see check if any feature needs to be dropped.

In [34]:
#function to calculate vif of features
def calculate_vif(df):
    vifData = pd.DataFrame()
    vifData['feature'] = df.columns
    vifData['vif'] = [variance_inflation_factor(df.values, i) for i in range(X.shape[1])]
    return vifData

Forward Selection by P-Value¶

Let's compare the previous linear model to another model created by forward selection using p-values.

In [47]:
#performs forward selection using p-values
predictorList = X

alpha = 0.05

selectedPredictors = []

while len(selectedPredictors) < len(predictorList):
    remaining_predictors = [p for p in predictorList if p not in selectedPredictors]

    pVal_list = []

    for predictor in remaining_predictors:
        loopFormula = f'bmi ~ {" + ".join(selectedPredictors + [predictor])}'

        model = smf.ols(formula = loopFormula, data = trainData).fit()

        pVal = model.pvalues[predictor]

        pVal_list.append((predictor, pVal))

    minPred, min_pVal = min(pVal_list, key=lambda x: x[1])

    if min_pVal < alpha:
        selectedPredictors.append(minPred)
        print(f'Added predictor: {minPred} with p-value: {min_pVal}')
    else:
        break

print("Selected Predictors:", selectedPredictors)

There are two striking issues in our diagnostic plots.

  1. For the Residuals vs. Fitted plot, there is a curved shape. Points on the left of the plot are mostly positive and/or near 0. There is also a slight trumpet shape. These indicate that the homoscedasticity assumption is violated by the model.

  2. In the Normal Q-Q plot, the tails are very heavy to the point that the plot is near vertical. This indicates that the normality assumption has been violated.

The Scale-Location plot is relatively spread out. There is a slight shape to it, which supports what we saw in the Residuals vs. Fitted plot. The Residuals vs. Leverage plot has one point on the outer border, but there are no extremely influential points.

OLS Regression Conclusion¶

In the models that we looked at we saw mediocre adjusted $R^2$ values and high $MSE$ values. Even after our feature engineering process (MSE ranking, backward elimination, and forward selction), the models all performed poorly. The diagnostic plots gave us some reasoning as to why they were poor. There are violations to homoscedasticity and normality assumptions that are required for OLS Regression.

We need to find more appropriate models. More specifically, we need to use models that are robust in regards to collinearity, heteroscedasticity, and lack of normality. We will switch our focus to Ensembles.

Ensemble Methods¶

Bagging with Random Forests and Boosting with XGBoost¶

In order to find a more accurate model, we will focus on Random Forests and XGBoost. Rather than using regression to predict bmi, we will go the classification route using obesity_class.

New $X$ and $y$ with Training and Testing Split¶

We will create a new $X$ and $y$ here. Since Random Forests are more robust, we can include more of our original features unlike our steps with OLS Regression. There is a risk of overfitting, but we can tune the hyperparameters to adjust for this. We can also split the data into training and testing sets.

In [53]:
#creates new X and y then splits into training and test sets
X = rf_df.drop(columns = ['obesity_class'])
y = rf_df['obesity_class']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 1)

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

We will adjust two hyperparameters. The first is setting max_features = 'sqrt'. This reduces the number of features considered when splitting and will help address overfitting. The second hyperparameter is the number of trees, i.e. n_estimators.

The following cell creates a list of values for n_estimators and loops through each value to find the corresponding accuracy.

In [54]:
#creates loop for random forest models with different estimator amounts
n_estimatorsList = [1, 10, 50, 100, 200, 300, 500, 750, 1000]

accuracyValues = []

for n in n_estimatorsList:
    rfClassifier = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = n, random_state = 1, max_features = 'sqrt')
    rfClassifier.fit(X_train, y_train)

    y_pred = rfClassifier.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

    accuracyValues.append(accuracy)

    print(f'Accuracy with {n} estimators: {accuracy}')

XGBoost Classification¶

Next we will use XGBoost for classification. We first need to make some changes to our target variable. XGBoost requires that the target variable be in integer format for categories. We will map the categories in an ordinal fashion.

In [59]:
#remaps the target variable column to align with xgboost format
targetMap = {'Underweight': 0, 'Normal': 1, 'Overweight': 2, 'Obesity_I': 3, 'Obesity_II': 4, 'Obesity_III': 5}
data_xgb = dataFinal.applymap(lambda x: targetMap.get(x, x))

New $y$ with Training and Testing Split¶

We can use the same $X$ as before. We have a new $y$ since we had to adjust the categories in the target variable column. Note, that since X is identical and there are still the same number of rows, the random_state parameter ensures that the training and testing sets are the same for both the Random Forest sets and the XGBoost sets.

In [60]:
#creates new y the splits data for training and testing sets
y = data_xgb['obesity_class']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 1)

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

We will adjust subsample and colsample_bytree. By making the subsample ratio smaller and by reducing the number of features for each tree, we can try to prevent overfitting. Just like we did in the Random Forest section, we will also tune n_estimators by using a loop through different values.

In [61]:
#creates loop for xgboost models with different estimator amounts
accuracyValuesXGB = []

for n in n_estimatorsList:
    xgbClassifier = xgb.XGBClassifier(n_estimators = n, random_state = 1, subsample = 0.5, colsample_bytree = 0.8)
    xgbClassifier.fit(X_train, y_train)

    y_pred = xgbClassifier.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

    accuracyValuesXGB.append(accuracy)

    print(f'Accuracy with {n} estimators: {accuracy}')

Conclusion¶

Best Model¶

Through our work we found that the XGBoost Model with 50 estimators is the best model in terms of accuracy and F1-score metrics. There was a thin margin in better performance when compared to the Random Forest model with 50 trees. One could also make the argument that the Random Forest model is a better option due to similar F1-scores and a higher Normal F1-score, though at a value of 0.61 that F1-score is still not amazing.

Difficulties and Takeaways¶

I think with every model there is a little bit of difficulty when dealing with parameters and hyperparameters. The trade-off of better performance vs. overfitting is a tricky balancing act.

When choosing this dataset I knew that it would be difficult making predictions and classifications based off of survey data. If I was able to investigate this problem further and collect more data myself, I would change how the data is collected and reported. There were too many options for each feature. Also, many questions were ambiguous and would only worsen response bias.

The OLS Regression models failed in this project. To improve, we would need to focus in on certain relevant features. Smoothing the terms or changing the regression type would involve more research, but it could work out to better performing models.

I learned more about ensemble methods during this project. I learned about applying an XGBoost model, which wasn't covered in the course. The random forest and XGBoost models helped reinforce what we learned throughout our assignments. These models could also be improved. There are numerous hyperparameters that could be tuned. Taking time to test many different options could lead to better results.

Ultimately, we achieved a model with an accuracy of approximately 78%. Considering that this was based on survey responses across many different weight/obesity categories, I am happy with it's performance.
